This is extremely random but I came across this picture a couple years ago
7:48 AM
7:48 AM
And it really stuck with me for some reason
7:49 AM
I have no idea where I even saw it or what it's from, but I really like the quote.
7:49 AM
And every now and then I'm reminded of it (like tonight) and I keep relating to it more and more
7:50 AM
People are so drawn to negativity and negative things for some reason. I often find myself surrounded by people constantly complaining about things - complaining about their day, complaining about their jobs, complaining about their friends, complaining about their family, complaining about... Everything... And I've just become numb to it. (edited)
7:51 AM
When I try to talk to people about things I love - about people I love, about hobbies that I love, about things I've done that I'm proud of, about games I enjoy... They always treat me like a neausance or like I'm wasting their time. They don't care to hear about those things.
7:52 AM
But whenever someone wants to tell a story about how much they hated some movie they watched recently, or when someone wants to complain about their day at work, or when someone wants to gossip about someone... People will sit and listen for hours.
OOPS! Studio! 2023-06-21 8:02 AM
I spend all my time on the things that I love. I learn about things that interest me, I play games that make me happy, I spend time with my friends, I work on projects that I'm proud of, I read about things that I'm curious about... I put so much effort into things I love - and I have nobody to share it with. Everybody around me would rather just complain. They watch the news and hear about things they hate and then come to me to vent about something that happened 4,000 miles away that doesn't affect them at all. Or they come home from work and complain about some weird person who came through the drivethrough while they were working. Or they read part of a book and then complain about how much they hate the author and go on a rant for 15 minutes about how stupid the book was. Or they buy a used puzzle from a thrift shop and complain that it's missing a piece and throw the whole thing away... It's like they're seeking out negativity and rejecting things that make them happy, and I don't know why. When I tell them about things that interest me they tell me it's "boring" or "dumb" or "a waste of time" but then they go hang out with their friends for 3 hours and come back with a bunch of negative feelings and unhappiness. They tell me all about how passionate they are about world history, but then just use it as an opportunity to complain about the fact that they can't afford the school they want to get into. When I asked them why they don't use the internet to explore their interest of history, they just complain about how the internet is no good and they can't trust anything they read, and they use it as an excuse to never spend a single minute learning about history while they mention every week how much they're "passionate" about it... I just don't understand. It's 2023 - the entire world is at their fingertips... Why can they not just do the things they enjoy instead of constantly seeking out unhappiness? (edited)
8:05 AM
If something makes me unhappy, I just avoid it... Why are so many people so drawn to things they hate?
8:06 AM
(Sorry. >-< I'm really bad at being concise. That is a lot of words to convey such a simple question...)
